<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Ulster committee debate allowed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government has allowed time for another Commons debate on the proposed
Northern Ireland select committee, signalling its determination to get the
new body up and running soon after Easter.
Next Tuesday's debate is needed because the planned composition of the
committee - widely seen as a reinforcement of the government's commitment to
Ulster's unionist majority - remains a bone of party political contention.
Labour objects to Tory proposals forced through the Commons selection
committee earlier this week which will limit its membership of the new body
to two MPs.
This compares with six Conservatives, four unionists and one member of the
mainly Catholic Social Democratic and Labour party. Opposition MPs are
expected to force several votes on Tuesday in a move to secure a more
favourable alignment of forces.
Meanwhile, Mr John Hume, the SDLP leader, yesterday urged republicans to
summon 'enormous courage' to abandon support for violence and engage in the
democratic effort to bring peace to the province.
He called on the IRA to lay down its guns and for Sinn Fein to enter the
talks process.
He said Ireland was at a crucial point in its history and that a search for
peace which included Dublin, Sinn Fein, nationalists and the Irish overseas
 -particularly those in the US - offered no threat to unionists.
If proposals are allowed to stand, select committee members will include Sir
James Kilfedder, the Ulster Popular Unionist MP for North Down and front
runner for chairman, and Mr Andrew Hunter, the pro-unionist chairman of the
Conservative backbench Northern Ireland committee.
Other committee members would be Conservatives Mr James Cran, Mr Charles
Hendry, Mr Richard Spring, Mr David Wilshire and Mr Mark Wolfson; Labour's
Mr Jim Marshall and Mr Clive Soley Mr Eddie McGrady (SDLP), Mr Ken Maginnis
and Mr John Taylor (UUP), and Mr Peter Robinson (DUP).
Today's planned visit to Northern Ireland by Mrs Mary Robinson, the Irish
president, drew attacks yesterday from unionist politicians, who described
the decision as provocative and an insult to the Queen.
</TEXT>
