<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Heseltine 'damaging Post Office' with delay in review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, was yesterday attacked
by MPs for damaging the Post Office by prolonging his review of its future.
The Commons trade and industry committee, which has a Conservative majority,
added to the cabinet debate over whether to exclude radical measures from
next year's legislative programme by urging Mr Heseltine to publish the
conclusions of the review and plans for any legislative action 'without
delay'.
Sir Cranley Onslow, a former chairman of the 1922 committee of Tory
backbenchers, said: 'What we are saying is we want to see a bill in the next
session.'
Mr Heseltine has said that there is a strong economic case for privatising
the Royal Mail - the Post Office's letters division - but has indicated that
political considerations have prevented him from doing so.
Many Tory backbenchers, particularly those threatened by Liberal Democrats
in the south-west of England, are worried about the impact of privatisation
on rural postal services.
A report by the committee, published yesterday, did not give its own
proposals on the Post Office's future - so hiding party political divisions.
Mr Keith Hampson, a Tory member of the committee, indicated that he favoured
privatising the Royal Mail, while Labour's Mr Michael Clapham argued that
the three Post Office divisions - Royal Mail, Parcelforce and Post Office
Counters - should be kept together.
The committee pinned the blame for uncertainty over the corporation's future
on Mr Heseltine, saying: 'It would appear that no new information or
research is awaited, only ministerial decisions.'
It said that while the review - which has lasted 20 months and cost Pounds
1.3m - continues, 'the Post Office has seen competitors attack its core
markets, but has been unable to fight back because, as a public sector body,
it faces government restrictions on its activities'.
'The growth of competition is made particularly harmful to the Post Office
by the uncertainty over its future,' it added.
The committee supported the Post Office's contention that it should be free
to raise money without being constrained by the public sector borrowing
requirement.
The Future of the Post Office. HMSO. Pounds 12.15.
</TEXT>
