<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Number of foreign banks in London exceeds 500
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The number of foreign banks in London topped 500 for the first time last
year, enhancing the capital's status as Europe's most significant financial
centre.
According to a survey by Noel Alexander Associates, a consultancy which
specialises in financial statistics, the 15 foreign banks that disappeared
from London - either through leaving or through mergers and takeovers - were
more than offset by the 35 which arrived.
There are 514 foreign banks in London.
The survey, which is published each year, reflects the changes to
international banking in London, with much of the activity coming from
eastern Europe and Asia.
Two of the new banks that opened were from Russia; two from the Czech
republic; one from former Yugoslavia, and one from Slovenia. Two were from
China, three from Hong Kong and one from Thailand.
Six of the 15 banks which disappeared did so as a result of mergers and
takeovers. Western European banks accounted for five of these, with the
remaining one being the takeover of the Canadian Royal Trust Bank by Royal
Bank of Canada.
Seven of the nine banks that actually left were from western Europe.
Last year also saw the first increase in the number of US banks in London
since 1982, as four US banks opened in the City.
Even so, this only takes the total back to its 1991 level of 49, which
itself was lower than every year since 1971.
The number of Japanese banks also rose again slightly, after a drop of two
in 1992, to reach 54 in total.
Noel Alexander says that London has a higher number of foreign banks than
any other city, including New York and Tokyo.
New Foreign Bank Offices in London. Noel Alexander, 6 Broad Street Place,
Blomfield Street, London, EC2M 7JU. Pounds 65
</TEXT>
