<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Britain opposed to milk quota cut
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain is to resist European Commission proposals for a 1 per cent cut in
its common agricultural policy milk quota from April 1, Mrs Gillian
Shephard, agriculture minister, told the Commons last night.
She said the existing quota was insufficient and a further reduction would
deal 'a severe blow' to the British dairy industry. Her pledge was welcomed
by MPs on both sides of the Commons.
Mrs Shephard insisted that such a reduction was not justified by the
Commission's own analysis of the market. Nor was it necessary to meet
obligations imposed by the general agreement on tariffs and trade.
Britain, which had fought against the use of quotas in the first place, was
ideally suited to produce milk and wanted the jobs that were provided
through the manufacture of milk products.
Mrs Shephard said the proposed cuts would have an adverse impact on the
European Union's 1995 budget, largely because of the effect on the beef
sector and the need to provide a compensation package for producers.
Mr Gavin Strang, shadow agriculture minister, warned that some multinational
companies were threatening to switch investment elsewhere because they
feared there would not be sufficient milk available for the high-value
products they wished to make in Britain.
</TEXT>
