<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Anger at Scottish council's Elf loan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Orkney Islands Council has agreed to make an interest-free loan of Pounds
15m to help the oil company Elf Enterprise win new business in the North Sea
for its Flotta oil terminal on Orkney.
The loan, believed to be unprecedented, sparked anger in Orkney yesterday.
The money will go toward funding a project to bring gas condensate and
natural gas liquids from the Britannia field. Chevron and Conoco, which will
operate the field, have yet to decide how and where to transport its output.
The Pounds 15m will come from Orkney Council's harbour equalisation fund,
set up in the 1970s to accumulate revenues from the Flotta terminal and
prolong its life. The fund stands at about Pounds 60m.
The Flotta terminal receives oil from Elf Enterprise's Piper and Claymore
fields, as well as some smaller fields. Although it is handling between
310,000 and 315,000 barrels of oil a day, the flow is expected to decline
early in the next decade.
The fund was set up to help keep the terminal running after the flow of oil
has fallen to an uneconomic level.
Chevron and Conoco expect the Britannia field to come into production by the
end of 1998. They have the choice of piping the condensate either to Flotta
or to Cruden Bay, Aberdeenshire.
An alternative is to order a concrete instead of a steel production
platform. This would enable the condensate to be stored under the plaform
and shipped out in tankers, a solution unlikely to involve Flotta.
Orkney Council said the loan would be spent on building a spur pipeline from
Brittannia to the Flotta pipeline. The loan, which it said was being made at
Elf Enterprise's request, is guaranteed by a consortium of banks and is
dependent on the success of the move to bring Britannia's output to Flotta.
Mr Iain Macdonald, a council member, said other councillors had agreed to
the loan after minimal consultation. 'We were railroaded,' he said.
Elf Enterprise indicated that both it and the council had an interest in
prolonging the life of the terminal.
</TEXT>
