<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / 'Technofear' hits used car prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Used car buyers are coming to fear expensive new technology so much that
standard models are starting to have a higher resale value than
top-specification vehicles of the same type, a senior executive of Glass's
Guide, the used car values directory, said yesterday.
Mr Leslie Allen, director and managing editor of the guide - regarded as the
motor trade's bible - also predicted that the higher resale value of diesel
cars compared with their petrol counterparts will have been eliminated by
the middle of next year, as supply and demand for diesel cars came into
balance.
Glass's conclusions about growing technophobia in the used car market are
potentially very bad news both for volume carmakers, which earn high margins
on vehicles laden with electronic systems, and executive and luxury
carmakers.
Volume producers already face having to make less well-equipped new cars
because of new company car tax legislation, effective next month, which
links employees' personal tax bills directly with cars' list prices.
The trend can only be accelerated by the prospect of steeper falls in
residual values of high-specification models if used car buyers - almost
always private motorists - shun them as the cars move from company fleets to
dealer forecourts.
It may also increase the depreciation rate of executive and luxury cars,
typically loaded with complex electronic systems such as traction control
and multi-mode automatic gearboxes which private motorists fear will be
expensive if they break down. Electronic control modules alone for such
systems can cost several hundred pounds.
Mr Allen said: 'We have reached the threshold of the ridiculous state where
a bog-standard Carlton, for example, will make more money than the
all-singing and dancing version.'
</TEXT>
