<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Coal bill provokes wrath of landowners
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Conservative party faces a protest campaign from some of its most
traditional supporters - owner-occupier farmers and landed gentry - over the
government's policies on state industry sell-offs.
The Country Landowners' Association yesterday threatened to 'hound and
harass' the government over the coal industry privatisation bill because of
its 'creeping erosion of land and property rights'. The CLA, with 50,000
members in England and Wales, is angry at the way the government has passed
compulsory powers of access to and acquisition of land from publicly owned
industries to the private sector.
The bill's present provisions have heightened that concern, and the CLA is
urging members to protest to Conservative associations.
'Our members are getting fed up with subsidising shareholders in what were
once publicly owned industries,' said Mr John Henderson, vice chairman of
the CLA's Yorkshire branch, its largest.
'There is a case for compulsory powers where land is needed for the public
good, but privatisation should not mean a licence to rip off private
landowners to subsidise dividends paid to shareholders of private
companies.'
Mr Henderson - chairman of the Coal Liaison Group, set up by the CLA and
others to try to amend the coal bill - said he did not think the government
understood the anger among his members. 'Let's have a level playing field
for all concerned,' he said.
</TEXT>
