<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Lib Dems reveal Tory poll fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Liberal Democrats yesterday sought to undermine the morale of
Conservative activists gathering for a weekend conference by unveiling a
leaked document revealing alarm within the Tory party over the Liberal
Democrat threat.
The 16-page document, written by a Conservative Central Office researcher
shortly after the 1992 general election, states that the 'Liberal Democrats
in the 1990s have to be taken as a serious threat by both the two major
parties'.
It says that Conservatives 'must wake up to the fact that no seat in the
whole of the south-west can any longer be taken for granted as 'safe'', and
that the Liberal Democrat resurgence means the Conservative party 'is faced
with the very real threat of losing its majority at the next general
election'.
Mr Matthew Taylor, Liberal Democrat chairman of campaigns, said yesterday
that the document showed how concerned the Tories were about prospects in
the forthcoming local and European elections.
The release of the research paper coincides with the start of the annual
Conservative Central Council in Plymouth, seen as an opportunity for Tory
managers to take their election campaign into the Liberal Democrat
heartland.
Mr Taylor said the document showed why the Tories were convening in
Plymouth. 'That is why they are attacking us on a daily basis, why we
believe they are right to be worried,' he said.
The research document predicts that, in the European elections in June this
year, the Euro seats of Cornwall and Plymouth, and Somerset and Dorset West
would be 'very vulnerable: on the basis of 1992 voting the Liberal Democrats
require only a 5 per cent swing to take either of them'.
Yesterday, Sir Norman Fowler, Conservative party chairman, accused the
Liberal Democrats of being 'Labour's bedfellows' and 'leftwing
opportunists'. He told journalists in London that the Liberal Democrats were
'a party of the left for the left'. He added: 'Like Labour, their activists
and MPs remain committed to higher taxes, higher spending, more state
intervention and greater union power.'
The counter-attack will not disguise the difficulties the Conservatives face
in Plymouth, with the conference certain to be dominated by the growing
storm over Britain's voting powers in an enlarged European Union.
</TEXT>
