<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Equality law audit breaches shown
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Many British companies are breaking the law by failing to provide adequate
information on equal opportunities policies in their annual accounts, three
academics said yesterday.
From a sample of 100 companies, 34 fully complied with disclosures required
by law on policy towards disabled employees while 14 made no mention of the
disabled at all. The findings were presented by Ms Carol Adams, Mr Andrew
Coutts and Mr George Harte at the annual British Accounting Association
conference at King Alfred's College in Winchester. They found that the Post
Office, with nearly one page, provided the most detail on equal
opportunities. The average length was just 0.13 of a page. Among businesses
which provided scant information on disabled employees were General
Electric, British Airways and British Telecommunications. Very few companies
described issues such as career breaks, flexible contracts or paternity
leave.
Most did not show the composition of the workforce by ethnic background or
monitoring policy. The conference heard that auditors who tender for work
and are tied to a fixed-fee contract are less likely to discover material
mis-statements in company accounts.
The survey - based on 70 Australian auditors - showed detection rose as the
length of client relationship increased.
</TEXT>
