<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Job cuts claim at Swans rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Receivers at Swan Hunter, the Tyneside shipbuilder, last night rejected a
statement from union officials that a further 490 jobs at the yard would be
shed in May. The possibility of the job losses had been discussed earlier
this week at a meeting of full-time union officials and staff of Price
Waterhouse, the receivers.
Mr Gordon Horsfield, joint receiver, said: 'Nobody is denying there is the
risk of these job losses, which is why they formed the basis of the
discussion with the unions but by no means is it definite.'
The receivers will seek meetings with union officials today to clarify the
situation.
The reason for the potential cut of 380 blue-collar jobs and 110 staff posts
is the handing over on May 12 of HMS Northumberland, one of three Type 23
frigates that Swan Hunter was fitting out when it went into receivership in
May.
This leaves only one frigate in the yard, providing too little work for the
workforce of 1,038 - down from 2,500 when the receiver was called in.
Yesterday Swan Hunter submitted to the Ministry of Defence its tender for
the 18-month refit of the Sir Bedivere landing ship, a contract crucial to
the yard's survival. But even if it wins this work, for which it faces
competition from four other UK yards, it faces a gap of some months in which
it has much too little work to sustain the present workforce.
The receivers have described the remaining employees as the 'golden nugget'
which underpinned the yard's saleability as a going concern. A near-halving
of this number would raise questions about Swan Hunter's potential to
survive as a large shipbuilder.
Mr Horsfield said job sharing, layoffs, subcontracting and the possibility
of finding other work were among the avenues being explored in the hope of
averting the 490 losses.
Negotiations between French-owned Constructions Mecaniques de Normandie and
the receivers, which began in London on Wednesday, continued yesterday.
CMN had hoped to make a firm bid for Swan Hunter, conditional on the company
winning the Sir Bedivere order, before the tender for the refit was
submitted yesterday. But last night, Price Waterhouse said there were 'loose
ends' still to be sorted out and it was likely to take two to three weeks to
reach any contractual commitment with CMN.
</TEXT>
