<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Judge aims to cure immunity system: The attorney-general is
under siege about the advice he gave to ministers over public interest
immunity certificates in the Matrix Churchill affair. John Mason reports
that far-reaching reform of the government's powers to suppress official
information now seems inevitable
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Whatever the future job prospects of Sir Nicholas Lyell, the
attorney-general, it is clear that the Scott inquiry will lead to a thorough
overhaul of the government's use of public interest immunity (PII) to
control publication of official information.
The immediate aftermath of the Matrix Churchill trial led to accusations
that ministers had sought to use PII - the application to a judge for
approval not to disclose information - to protect the government by
preventing publication of embarrassing material in spite of it clearly being
of help to those in the dock.
Sir Nicholas yesterday dismissed this interpretation of events as 'utterly
untrue'. But the tense exchanges between himself and Lord Justice Scott
provided an extraordinary demonstration that two of the most senior legal
figures in the country could barely agree on anything about the application
of this controversial procedure.
This follows on from the admissions made to the inquiry by two figures
involved in the Matrix Churchill PII claims.
Mr Gerald Hosker, the Treasury solicitor, said that proper procedures had
not been adhered to and backed calls for reform of PII to apply it only in
limited circumstances.
Mr Alan Moses QC, the barrister who brought the prosecution for Customs &amp;
Excise, said the use of PII had damaged public confidence in the criminal
justice system. PII procedure, he agreed, had to be changed.
In yesterday's exchanges, the main dispute concerned whether ministers have
any discretion to sign PII certificates.
Sir Nicholas began by maintaining that such discretion did not exist, except
in rare cases. It was for the trial judge alone to take the decision. It was
this advice he had given Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary,
who was originally reluctant to sign his certificate.
The exception, Sir Nicholas said in a statement at the start of the hearing,
was based upon a ruling in a civil case in 1989. He said this allowed
ministers the discretion not to apply for PII 'where there is a clear
balance in favour of disclosure in the interests of justice'.
But he added: 'This exception must not be invoked lightly. It would be wrong
for the minister to rely upon it unless advised by counsel, who will
inevitably have a far greater familiarity with the issues in the case, that
there is indeed a clear balance in favour of disclosure.'
Lord Justice Scott was insistent in probing whether ministers should
ultimately decide if there was a serious risk of damage to the public
interest before applying for PII.
Before 1968, the courts had no power to challenge a minister's assertion
that documents should not be disclosed. The House of Lords then made two
crucial rulings - first, that such claims could be challenged in the courts,
and second, that the government could use classes of privilege to apply for
PII. These classes cover areas such as national security, the identity of
informers and advice to ministers.
The rulings allowed the challenging of ministers' judgments, but the ability
to use class immunity has since been a means of applying for PII over an
increasingly wide range of documents.
Lord Justice Scott and Sir Nicholas clashed on a 1989 ruling by Lord Justice
Bingham that ministers have a duty to assert PII that cannot be waived. But
the ruling also allowed for voluntary disclosure where the public interest
was plainly in favour of it. It is this which provides the exception that
Sir Nicholas agreed could allow ministers to use their discretion.
It was on this point, under pressure from an increasingly irate judge, that
the attorney-general apparently shifted his position.
A minister would take advice from prosecuting counsel over whether
disclosure was plainly in the interests of justice, he said. However, he
admitted, a minister remained able to ignore the barrister's advice and
decide to disclose documents if he felt this appropriate. This admission
appeared to contradict what he had said in his opening statement two hours
previously.
However, after the lunchtime news headlines said he had back-tracked on his
main argument, Sir Nicholas issued a second statement. Matrix Churchill had
not been one of these exceptional cases and his advice to Mr Heseltine
remained correct, he said.
If ministerial discretion dominated these exchanges, the class immunity
system has caused equal alarm among lawyers. To legal observers, the most
telling evidence given to the inquiry on this subject was provided by Mr
Andrew Leithead, an assistant Treasury solicitor involved in the Matrix
Churchill claims.
The government was always 'generous' in the range of documents for which it
sought to claim PII and only the most trivial of documents should not be
subjected to claims, he said. The confidentiality of the Whitehall
decision-making process had to be protected as a matter of principle, he
said.
It was this illustration of how Whitehall operates that alarmed many
observers.
One defence solicitor responded: 'It was the clearest demonstration that,
when Whitehall thinking is allowed to go to extremes, it completely fails to
allow for common sense - or any appreciation of the world outside the civil
service. It is quite, quite, terrifying.'
It seems certain that Lord Justice Scott will recommend that the government
reforms PII. Within the criminal bar there is widespread agreement that
these recommendations must be far-reaching and concentrate on reducing the
amount of information withheld to the bare minimum.
Mr Roy Amlot QC, a leading defence silk and former Treasury counsel, said:
'He (Lord Justice Scott) will certainly go to town on procedure and tighten
ministerial responsibility. The first essential is that it should no longer
be possible to use classes of documents to claim PII. He must insist it is
only claimed on a document-by-document basis and only when there is a
genuine public interest against disclosure.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
