FT  25 MAR 94 / Smith to paint Labour as a friend of small business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Smith will today portray Labour as the friend of small business when
he maps out a raft of ideas for improving the flow of investment to the
sector.
The Labour leader will use a speech to small business leaders in Edinburgh
to argue that his party and the sector are 'natural allies' in the battle to
create new jobs.
He will emphasise that Labour shares the sector's worries about red tape and
that it will 'happily get rid of any regulations that are pointless and out
of date'.
Mr Smith will underline Labour's support for the creation of a statutory
right for companies to charge interest on overdue debts.
Referring to a need to devise ways of channelling money towards small firms,
Mr Smith will say that Labour would seriously consider setting up a
private-sector managed investment fund focusing on small business.
According to Mr Smith, Labour also believes there is a 'strong case' for
expanding the small business loan guarantees scheme.
A document covering Labour's proposed approach to industry, which it is
planning for this year's conference, is to contain a chapter on small
business, Mr Smith will announce.
