<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Jailed adviser is banned by SIB
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Securities and Investments Board has indefinitely banned from the
securities industry Mr Christopher Fallon, who is serving a nine-month
prison sentence.
Mr Fallon is the second person banned from securities or investment
activities under Section 59 of the Financial Services Act. The first was Mr
Roger Levitt, who was convicted of fraud charges and who received a
non-custodial sentence.
Mr Fallon, who operated Fallon and Co, based in north London, had presented
himself as an expert in futures and options. But he was not authorised to
conduct investment business.
Last July, SIB, the City's chief regulatory watchdog, secured an injunction
barring him from conducting investment business after it was discovered that
he was giving advice. Mr Fallon then breached that injunction by taking
Pounds 24,000 from two individuals.
The watchdog then applied to the High Court for a prison sentence for
violating the injunction. That request was granted last week, and he was
jailed for contempt.
The Pounds 24,000 has not been recovered and because Mr Fallon was not
authorised to conduct investment business, the investors will not be allowed
to make claims upon the Investors Compensation Scheme.
SIB said it viewed the case as evidence that civil prosecution could secure
more punitive terms for wrongdoers in certain cases than a criminal
prosecution could.
At least four other Section 59 cases are pending before SIB. Individuals
charged in such cases have the right to appeal against a decision and seek a
hearing.
</TEXT>
