<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Mexican Crisis: Mexico's violence claims a rare victim from
politics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Luis Donaldo Colosio was shot as he was leaving a campaign rally in the
sprawling city of Tijuana, the fourth largest in Mexico, just over the
border from San Diego.
He was Mexico's first presidential candidate to be assassinated since
President-elect Alvara Obregon was murdered in 1928. Since then Mexico had
enjoyed remarkable political stability, with every president having lived
out his term, peacefully handing power over to his successor.
Inevitably there was speculation that the assassination, coming so soon
after the New Year's peasant uprising in the state of Chiapas, had been
planned by groups that were set on damaging the Mexican government, or
seeking to replace Mr Colosio with a presidential candidate more favourable
to their interests.
As of yesterday there was no evidence of any conspiracy. Police in Tijuana
arrested Mario Aburto Martinez for the killing. Mr Aburto, 23, an industrial
mechanic, had been grabbed by eyewitnesses and dragged to the nearest police
station. Police have not linked Mr Aburto to any group.
The Attorney-General's office said Mr Aburto confessed to the killing in the
presence of local lawyers, and to buying the pistol several weeks ago with
the purpose of assassinating Mr Colosio. It said it had forensic proof Mr
Aburto had shot twice from a .38 pistol. Police investigations were
continuing. According to the Attorney-General's Office, Mr Aburto said he
was a pacifist, and claimed to have written several books.
The police also detained a second man, Vicente Mayoral, although it appeared
he was just a witness to the shooting.
Given the widespread violence in Mexico, and the few security precautions
politicians take, it was remarkable that so long had passed without such a
political assassination. In 1990 Mexico suffered 30.7 murders per 100,000
people, more than Brazil, and compared with 13.3 in the US.
Last year drug traffickers accidentally killed Cardinal Juan Jesus Posadas
of Guadalajara in a shoot-out with a rival gang, according to the official
explanation. Last week an unknown group of men kidnapped Mr Alfredo Harp
Helu, co-head of Banamex, Mexico's largest bank.
Tijuana, a city whose population, thanks to migration and economic
integration with the US, has nearly tripled in 20 years to an official
900,000, is one of Mexico's most violent cities. Long known for its sleazy
bars and nightclubs, it has more recently become a centre for drug
traffickers, and home to thousands of factories, and the shanty towns that
surround them.
Mr Colosio was on the edge of one of the shanty town when giving his last
speech. Like all Mexican politicians he though nothing of mingling with the
crowd after giving his speech. That will now change.
</TEXT>
