FT  25 MAR 94 / Leaked letter upset for ANC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MATTHEW CURTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A leaked letter of intent sent by the South African government to the
International Monetary Fund last year threatens to embarrass the African
National Congress.
The ANC put its name to a document committing a new government to fiscal and
monetary discipline as a precondition for securing a five-year Dollars 850m
(Pounds 574m) loan for drought relief.
Mr Alec Erwin, a leading ANC parliamentary candidate, this week argued
against rigid deficit ceilings, in favour of greater flexibility.
But Mr Tito Mboweni, the ANC's representative on the Transitional Executive
Council's finance committee, said it regarded the IMF letter of intent as
'binding'.
The letter, signed by the TEC, the multiparty body overseeing government,
recognises the importance of tight monetary policy, and states that
'increases in government deficit would jeopardise the economic future of the
country'.
