<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / World Trade News: US fails to put worker rights on WTO
agenda
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A US attempt to put worker rights on the negotiating agenda of the new World
Trade Organisation was rebuffed by trading partners yesterday.
Trade negotiators rejected a demand for a reference to the link between
labour standards and trade to go into the political declaration being
drafted for ministers to endorse when they meet next month in Marrakesh to
sign the Uruguay Round trade liberalising accords. 'The US had no support at
all,' said one trade official at the talks.
While the European Union in principle favours a discussion of the worker
rights issue, it did not back the US in requesting specific language in the
draft ministerial declaration.
In any event, this could never have won the support of developing countries,
especially in Asia, which are strongly opposed to labour and human rights
appearing on the trade agenda. They fear that such moves will provide new
pretexts for trade protection in the industrialised world.
Washington must now decide whether to give in and allow an agreed draft
ministerial declaration to go forward without a reference to worker rights,
or stand its ground at the risk of precipitating a row at Marrakesh.
A meeting of the trade negotiations committee, which supervises the
120-nation Uruguay Round, is scheduled for next Wednesday when all the
agreements, decisions and declarations for the Marrakesh meeting are
supposed to be finalised.
Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade representative, said on Wednesday that the
Clinton administration would be seeking some understanding at Marrakesh on
the need for labour standards to be addressed.
'What we are trying to achieve is to tie internationally recognised labour
standards to trade,' he told a House of Representatives commerce
sub-committee.
</TEXT>
