<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Prudential refuses to join retail investment watchdog
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Prudential Corporation, the UK's largest life insurer, has rejected the
prospect of joining the Personal Investment Authority, the new regulator to
protect private investors.
It is insisting instead on its right to come directly under the Securities
and Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog.
That brings Prudential into direct conflict with the regulators, since Mr
Andrew Large, SIB chairman, has made it clear it wanted to end SIB's role in
direct regulation of retail financial services.
In a strongly worded statement, Mr Mick Newmarch, Prudential chief
executive, said Prudential did not believe the PIA's approach to regulation
was suited to providing 'adequate and cost-effective saver protection'.
It had concluded that the option of statutory regulation by the SIB was more
consistent with its point of view and in the best interests of its
customers, Mr Newmarch said.
From July, the PIA is intended to be the single watchdog for retail
financial services, replacing the existing system of separate regulators for
different types of organisation, such as independent financial advisers and
life companies.
Mr Newmarch said the fact that the PIA had not yet developed its own
rulebook, but planned to begin its work as a regulator using the rules of
the existing regulators, seemed to involve 'giving a blank cheque to PIA
when nothing in its history justifies that level of confidence'.
At an earlier stage, such a stark challenge to the prospects for the PIA
might have derailed the new regulator. But with less than a fortnight to go
before the first deadline for applications, and some previous critics - such
as Standard Life and Scottish Amicable - making it clear they will join, the
PIA still appears poised to go ahead. Halifax, the UK's largest building
society, earlier this week expressed serious reservations and said it had
not decided whether to apply.
The Prudential's decision was greeted with statements of regret by the SIB,
the PIA and the government.
The Treasury response underlined ministers' continuing determination not to
be pushed into legislating for a full-blown statutory system of regulation -
as Prudential would prefer.
It expressed full support for the SIB's approach and added: 'Neither the PIA
nor its timetable will be in any way deflected by the Pru's decision.'
In practice, the SIB will be able to delegate the routine regulation to the
PIA and can apply PIA standards. But it will still have to carry out its own
disciplinary proceedings.
Editorial Comment, Page 19
Insurers admit role in pension fears survey, Page 10
