<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Mexico in crisis after killing: Political turmoil after
assassination of the ruling PRI party candidate Colosio
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER and STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mexico has been thrown into political turmoil by the assassination of Mr
Luis Donaldo Colosio, the presidential candidate of the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary party (PRI).
The death of Mr Colosio, who was shot in the head and chest late on
Wednesday in the border city of Tijuana, heightened fears of instability
just weeks after an Indian rebellion in the southern state of Chiapas and
after months of economic stagnation.
Mexico's attorney-general said yesterday that Mario Aburto Martinez, 23, had
admitted to the killing, although his motive was not yet known. Mr Aburto, a
mechanic arrested at the scene, had claimed to be a pacifist.
Despite the closure of Mexico's financial markets yesterday, the price of
Mexican shares and bonds fell sharply in London and New York, although they
recovered from their lows. New York analysts said prices of New York-quoted
Mexican shares suggested a fall of 4-5 per cent in the Mexican stock market.
However, last night the US set up a Dollars 6bn (Pounds 4bn) credit line to
help Mexico weather financial jitters when markets reopen today.
The PRI, or more likely in practice President Carlos Salinas de Gortari,
will have to select a new presidential candidate for this August's election.
Under Mexico's constitution, officials are not permitted to run for the
presidency if they have held government office in the six months before the
elections. This means that unless the constitution is changed, no member of
the current cabinet could run.
This would leave Mr Ernesto Zedillo, former education minister and Mr
Colosio's campaign manager, as the front-runner. Although Mr Zedillo is
considered politically inexperienced, his chances of being chosen as the
PRI's new candidate improved last night when another leading contender, Mr
Manuel Camacho, the peace envoy to the troubled southern state of Chiapas,
said he would not stand.
However, Dr Ignacio Burgoa, professor emeritus of law at the National
Autonomus University of Mexico, says the government, with the support of at
least one opposition party, could muster enough votes to change the
constitution in 10 to 15 days. That would enable Mr Pedro Aspe, finance
minister, and a host of other cabinet ministers to run.
Mexico's ruling party has been in power for 65 years, and Mr Colosio was the
favourite to win the August elections. A former social development minister
and president of the PRI, he represented continuity with the economic and
political policies of President Salinas.
The new candidate will be weakened by being the party's second choice, and
will have just five months to set up his campaign. Democratic reforms,
passed by Congress on Wednesday night, go a long way in letting the
opposition compete on equal terms with the PRI, making elections potentially
the most competitive in the nation's history. On the other hand, the
sympathy felt for the PRI after Mr Colosio's assassination may lead to an
increase in support.
Mr Salinas appealed to Mexicans for calm and unity, and appeared to rule out
the possibility of a state of emergency.
The assassination of Mr Colosio comes in a period of unusual political
instability, and the possibility of a conservative backlash was being aired
yesterday. Many Mexicans saw a link between the peasant uprising in Chiapas,
last week's kidnapping of Mr Alfredo Harp Helu, the co-head of Mexico's
largest bank, and Mr Colosio's murder.
Mexico's economy has also been vulnerable in recent weeks, with the peso
having depreciated sharply against the dollar as the government sought to
boost a stagnant economy. The Bank of Mexico is expected to defend the peso
today when markets reopen.
Murder raises spectre of political instability, Page 8
An economy vulnerable to unrest, Page 8
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
