FT  24 MAR 94 / International Company News: JP Morgan chairman paid Dollars
6.6m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Dennis Weatherstone, chairman of JP Morgan, the US bank, was paid Dollars
6.6m last year, a rise of 45 per cent on 1992 and an echo of other big pay
rises in the US financial sector announced recently.
Morgan said Mr Weatherstone's remuneration, in the form of Dollars 3.1m cash
and Dollars 3.5m of restricted shares, reflected the bank's 'very strong
earnings' during 1993.
The New York-based institution, one of the most profitable commercial banks
in the country, made after-tax earnings of Dollars 1.73bn, up from Dollars
1.13bn the year before.
The British-born Mr Weatherstone, who has headed the bank since 1990, was
paid a base salary of Dollars 700,000, with the rest of his income linked to
performance.
Among other high-paid bank chairmen, Mr John Reed of Citicorp received
Dollars 6.2m, nearly three times his remuneration the year before, while Mr
Dan Tully, chairman of Merrill Lynch, received Dollars 9.6m, a rise of 30
per cent.
US financial companies benefited last year from favourable financial
markets, a beneficial interest rate environment and the effects of a
gathering recovery in US economy.
