FT  24 MAR 94 / International Company News: Volvo appoints new truck chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Volvo, Sweden's biggest manufacturer, yesterday appointed a new head for its
truck division.
Mr Sten Langenius, who built Volvo into one of the world's top truck makers,
is to step aside after 17 years and will be succeeded by Mr Karl-Erling
Trogen. It is the latest move in a review of senior management, begun since
it scrapped a plan to merge with France's Renault, which prompted the
resignation of its long-time chairman Mr Pehr Gyllenhammar.
Mr Trogen, head of Volvo's US truck operation, was to have been in charge of
truck operations in the ill-fated Renault-Volvo company.
Mr Langenius, soon to reach retirement, will remain a full-time executive at
Volvo as vice-president, with responsibility for the smaller marine engine
and aero engine divisions.
Another top Gyllenhammar executive, Mr Lennart Jeansson, was left without a
clear function by the collapse of the merger plan. He had given up his
position as head of the car division to Mr Per-Erik Mohlin in preparation to
become finance chief of Renault-Volvo.
Mr Soren Gyll, chief executive, said management functions within Volvo were
still under review.
