<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Darty helps Kingfisher to Pounds 309m: Analysts concerned
with retailer's underlying performance despite 51% rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Kingfisher shares fell yesterday in spite of better than expected results,
reflecting disappointment over the retailer's underlying performance in the
UK.
Pre-tax profits of Pounds 309.3m, a rise of 51 per cent, were about Pounds
10m ahead of expectations. Sales rose 26.3 per cent to Pounds 4.48bn.
The profits advance was largely fuelled by a Pounds 79.2m operating
contribution from Darty, the French electricals retailer acquired in
February last year for Pounds 1bn. Profits were further cushioned by a lower
than expected interest charge of Pounds 7.6m (Pounds 700,000) and a rise in
the property contribution from Pounds 8.1m to Pounds 43m.
Operating profits from the main UK retailing businesses, where Kingfisher
launched a strategy of everyday low pricing last year, fell 3 per cent.
One analyst described the returns from Comet, Woolworths, B&amp;Q and Superdrug
as 'a bit disappointing'. 'It would appear that the strategy is not
delivering great profit growth.'
The shares fell 9p to 561p, and have dropped 22 per cent since January's
trading statement after which analysts downgraded expectations from Pounds
315m to Pounds 300m. Analysts also indicated that 1995 forecasts would be
pulled back.
Sir Geoffrey Mulcahy, chairman, rejected criticism of the low price policy.
'It is designed to attack the lower growth and more competitive retail
environment of the 1990s,' he said. 'I am convinced that strategy is right
and it is working.'
Kingfisher has decided to step up introduction of electronic points of sale
throughout the group to cut costs and reinforce the strategy. Sir Geoffrey
said Epos would be in every store by the Christmas trading period.
He was pleased with the results, which had demonstrated the 'soundness of
both Kingfisher's businesses and its balance sheet'. Debt was reduced from
66 per cent of shareholders' funds to 33 per cent.
Darty had been 'particularly encouraging', said Sir Geoffrey, 'given the
recession in France'. The group had increased market share in an intensely
competitive environment, and deliberately avoided chasing lower-margin
volume.
The chairman would not comment on current trading. However, Kingfisher has
decided to make two trading statements a year in addition to announcing its
results. The next statement is due in June.
The dividend was raised 10 per cent to 10.5p, for a total 9 per cent higher
at 14.9p.
Fully diluted earnings rose 15 per cent to 36.9p.
Market report, Page 42; Details, Page 24; Lex, Page 22; Selling it cheap,
Page 17
</TEXT>
