<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Weak oil prices take toll on Lasmo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lasmo, one of the UK's largest oil exploration and production companies,
yesterday passed its final dividend as it struggled to come to terms with
continuing oil price weakness.
It reported a pre-tax loss of Pounds 9m, against a restated deficit of
Pounds 262m. After tax and dividend payments, the amount withdrawn from
reserves was Pounds 141m. The loss per share was 17.5p, reduced from 52.3p.
The group said the loss attributable to shareholders before exceptional
charges was Pounds 59m, compared with a Pounds 34m profit.
Mr Joe Darby, chief executive, said oil prices lingering around the Dollars
13-Dollars 14 a barrel level for Brent Blend constituted the 'exceptional
circumstances' that caused the board to chop the final dividend. It promised
last year to make a final 2p payout to equal the previous 3.3p total.
'We thought the 1.3p announced at the time of the interim results was
enough,' he said. The decision would save Pounds 20m cash. The future annual
dividend would be 1p, until 'an increase can be justified'.
Low oil prices caused the company to make a Pounds 120m provision against
assets including fields in Nova Scotia and Italy, and a new accommodation
platform at the UK Claymore field. UK tax changes allowed the release of
Pounds 45m provisions, leaving a net exceptional charge of Pounds 72m.
Turnover was Pounds 678m, up from Pounds 621m, as production rose 10 per
cent to 167,000 barrels a day of oil equivalent (including natural gas).
Operating profits totalled Pounds 110m, against Pounds 112m.
Lasmo's vulnerability to low prices was illustrated by an average cost of
sales of Pounds 8.15 a barrel, compared with current sterling price of about
Pounds 9.30. The company aims to trim unit operating costs of Pounds 4.10 a
barrel by 10 per cent this year and by 25 per cent in real terms over the
next four years. A shift towards lower cost production was highlighted by
yesterday's announcement of the Pounds 84m sale of Lasmo's interests in the
high-cost mature Ninian field in the North Sea.
Year-end gearing was reduced from 110 to 75 per cent, on net debt of Pounds
794m. The company has extensive development programmes, and Mr Darby
acknowledged that the target of keeping gearing to 80-90 per cent by 1995
was based on oil prices 'higher than they are today'.
Lex, Page 22; Details, Page 25
</TEXT>
