<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Halifax ready to cut mortgage rate if base rates fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Halifax building society, the UK's largest, said yesterday that if there
were a further 0.25 percentage point cut in base lending rates then it would
reduce its variable mortgage rates.
Announcing a 27 per cent increase in pre-tax profits to Pounds 866m for
1993-94, the chairman Mr Jon Foulds made it clear, however, that a cut in
rates to borrowers would also mean reductions for savers.
Halifax attracted Pounds 1.1bn in retail savings last year, taking retail
funds and deposits to Pounds 51.6bn, and raised a further Pounds 2.1bn on
the wholesale markets, where funding was cheaper.
Mr Foulds said the society had performed well in the 'fragile market',
although he acknowledged the fierce competition for retail savings. He
highlighted short-term factors such as payment of home fuel bills in advance
of the imposition of Value Added Tax in April, and more permanent features
such as the popularity of unit trusts and Peps.
The society's wholesale funding ratio, at 18.3 per cent of total shares,
deposits and loans, remained well within the statutory limit of 40 per cent.
In the longer term, however, he said the proportion of the balance sheet
from the wholesale markets would have to grow, and so societies would need
wider access to wholesale markets. This is one of the priorities for the
government's review of building society legislation.
Mr Foulds added that he thought there was a 'sea-change' in the pattern of
personal savings. This was one reason for the launch of Halifax Life next
January.
A sharp fall in provisions for bad and doubtful debts - mostly for
residential property - to Pounds 271m, from Pounds 374m in the year to the
end of January 1993, was one factor in the rise, but the level of
provisioning remained higher than in previous years. Mr Foulds believed
there would be significant levels of provisions for a few years to come,
though he was encouraged by the drop in arrears.
Gross lending rose to Pounds 8.6bn, from Pounds 8.3bn, while net lending
fell back slightly to Pounds 3.2bn from Pounds 3.3bn. This represented a
slightly larger share - 19 per cent - of a smaller mortgage market. The
number of advances rose to 1.86m from 1.82m.
The society's total assets rose by 6 per cent to Pounds 67bn. Its
cost/income ratio remained stable at just under 40 per cent.
Losses at Halifax's estate agency fell to Pounds 4m from Pounds 18m, and it
is expected to break even in the current year. Mr Mike Blackburn, chief
executive, said the agency provided 10 per cent of Halifax's mortgage
business, and would remain part of the society's strategy.
Mr Blackburn said Halifax had reservations about the Personal Investment
Authority, the watchdog to protect private investors, and had not yet
decided whether to join. It would prefer full statutory regulation and
doubted the PIA would deliver an increase in investor protection.
</TEXT>
