<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Whitehall's secrecy rules to be eased
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is to classify fewer documents 'top secret' in a shake-up of
its security system, and it claims that less information will be kept from
the public.
The move, which follows a review, could lead to substantial savings in the
annual Pounds 300m bill for Whitehall security.
Mr John Major announced yesterday that he had approved more detailed
definitions of the four categories by which sensitive documents are
classified. These are: top secret, secret, confidential and restricted.
The new system may help the government to allay criticisms of over-secretive
Whitehall practices that could emerge from the Scott inquiry into arms for
Iraq and which are at the heart of the investigation into the Pergau dam aid
deal with Malaysia.
The prime minister said the overhaul would 'allow fewer government documents
to be classified, particularly at the higher levels'. He also claimed that
the definitions and recent review of security measures would permit
'substantial cost savings' in vetting procedures.
At present, the 'top secret' classification is defined as 'causing
exceptionally grave damage to the interests of the nation'. It is to be
replaced by a longer definition which says that such information, if leaked,
would 'lead directly to widespread loss of life' or 'threaten directly the
internal stability of the UK or friendly countries'.
But pressure groups and opposition MPs were sceptical about whether the
changes would lead to more disclosure. Campaigners against official secrecy
said the reform would merely give Whitehall departments more elaborate
reasons to withhold information when a new Code of Practice on Government is
introduced in the next few days.
The code is being hailed by ministers as a breakthrough in freedom of
information, giving the public the right to request information on any
Whitehall department's activities.
But Mr Maurice Frankel, director of the Campaign for Freedom of Information,
said the new classifications would give officials better reasons for keeping
information secret. He emphasised that a department's decision not to
release information could not be challenged in the courts.
Mr Michael Meacher, shadow civil service minister, said: 'Not a single
document will be released or be more directly available as a result of this
feeble review.'
</TEXT>
