<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Richard Harris's comedy of manners, Outside Edge, with its weirdly assorted
couples coming together via the cricket pavilion, was a huge success on
stage, where Maureen Lipman played Maggie. Will it work as well now that
Harris has expanded it to a television series? We shall find out at 8.30
when ITV screens the first episode.
Cutting Edge Special investigates accidents at work and asks why inspectors
from the Health And Safety Executive refuse to prosecute individuals for
manslaughter (9.00 C4).
There have been good television drama series about the criminal underworld
in the US, Italy and Britain, so why not Russia? Brian Cox stars as the big
wheel in the St Petersburg Police, Grushko, whose name is the title of this
three-part mini series beginning on BBC1 (9.30).
Assassination and all kinds of violence in South Africa are routinely
attributed by white television producers to the heritage of apartheid. How,
then, do they explain assassination and violence in other African countries?
They don't. Beloved Country has another go at South Africa (9.30 BBC2).
</TEXT>
