<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Tax dodge measures slammed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Leading tax and accountancy professionals yesterday criticised proposed
legislation intended to stop tax avoidance through offshore companies.
The Institute of Taxation said measures in the finance bill were
over-complex, would impose large compliance costs on firms and give
undefined powers to the Inland Revenue.
Mr Malcolm Gammie, president of the Institute of Taxation, said: 'The cost
of complying with these new rules will hit everyone, not merely those
companies engaged in tax avoidance.'
Mr Tony Hughes, of accountants Coopers &amp; Lybrand, said: 'The government has
not listened to our concerns, which is very disappointing. But we note that
the Treasury will be setting up a working party into how the legislation
will operate.'
The criticism comes after MPs voted through clause 123 of the finance bill
on Tuesday. The clause closes a loophole in existing legislation which
protects against avoidance of UK tax by companies diverting income to
subsidiaries in low tax areas overseas.
Profits - which a foreign non-trading subsidiary must distribute to the UK
if it wishes to avoid charges under foreign company legislation - must now
be calculated on a tax rather than on an accounts basis.
The government says companies use accounting tricks to disguise profits,
costing the exchequer at least Pounds 50m each year. But leading companies
and accounting bodies complain that the new rules impose a heavy burden on
companies and they apply retrospectively.
Inland Revenue officials yesterday denied that clause 123 would be
retrospective and said that they were prepared to discuss new legislation
with tax practitioners and publish guidelines.
Last Thursday the government was forced to withdraw clause 241 of the
finance bill after pressure from politicians and tax and accounting bodies.
The clause would have increased the power of the Inland Revenue to seize
books and records.
Mr Gammie said: 'Both clauses are badly drafted and provide inadequate
safeguards against their exercise. If the Revenue needs extra powers it
should have them, but it is unclear and uncertain as to how far the
Revenue's powers extend. We are having to rely on the Revenue fulfilling
assurances made in private rather than on the record.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Government News.
</TP>
