<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Watchdog urged to probe education adverts spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's spending watchdog is to be asked to investigate allegations
that the Department for Education has 'misused' public funds in advertising
its policies.
Mr Robert Sheldon, Labour chairman of the Commons' Public Accounts
Committee, said he would ask the National Audit Office to investigate
spending on publicity at the department following a complaint from Mrs Ann
Taylor, shadow education secretary.
Mrs Taylor has written to Mr Sheldon claiming that the department's annual
expenditure on advertising had risen 8,000 per cent since the Conservatives
came to power - from Pounds 103,800 in 1979-80 to Pounds 8.9m in 1991-92.
'Without exception, parents complain of money being wasted which could
usefully be spent on schools,' Mrs Taylor said.
A submission to the NAO is usually the first step in a parliamentary
investigation of how public money is spent.
If the watchdog agrees to produce an official report, the committee can
investigate the matter, cross-examining ministers and officials.
The Liberal Democrats yesterday joined the attack, arguing that officials at
the department had broken their own code of practice in their recent
advertising campaign for the promotion of grant maintained schools. Mr Don
Foster, Liberal Democrat education spokesman, accused the department of
issuing 'biased advertisements' which implied that only governors and head
teachers of grant maintained schools had the power to make decisions on
their own expenditure - and that local education authority school governors
had no financial control.
'The adverts are a clear breach of practice in that the information is
presented in such a way as to be hugely misleading,' said Mr Foster.
'Ministers have been contradicting each other in an attempt to defend them.'
Mr Foster's complaint is being submitted to the parliamentary ombudsman.
</TEXT>
