<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Institutions boost investment levels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Investment by UK pension funds, insurance companies, investment and unit
trusts shot up last year, reflecting the rebuilding of personal savings and
a switch by savers away from cash to securities.
The Central Statistical Office said yesterday that total net investment by
institutions in 1993 was a record Pounds 52.2bn, compared with Pounds 35.8bn
in 1992.
It was also at a record Pounds 14.9bn in the fourth quarter of last year, up
from Pounds 13.6bn in the third.
'The figures show that the personal savings are there, and are finding their
way to the investment institutions,' said Mr Kevin Gardiner, UK economist at
Morgan Stanley. 'Consumers no longer want to hold their assets in the form
of money but want to put them into securitised savings.'
Particularly striking was a sharp jump in land and property investment in
the fourth quarter, a move that highlighted a decisive change in investors'
sentiments towards the UK property and land market.
Net investment in 'other' assets increased to Pounds 2.3bn in the three
months to December, reflecting investment of Pounds 1bn in UK land, property
and ground rent. This followed disinvestment in the previous two quarters.
Investment in UK company shares also rose from a net Pounds 4.1bn in the
third quarter to Pounds 4.9bn in the fourth. Institutions' net investment in
overseas securities rose from Pounds 3bn to Pounds 3.6bn.
Overall, the annual level of net investment in both UK and overseas company
securities increased substantially last year. For UK company shares the
amount rose from Pounds 8.1bn in 1992 to Pounds 20.9bn. After a
disinvestment of Pounds 0.5bn in overseas companies in 1992, flows last year
increased to Pounds 11.2bn.
Investment in UK government bonds, or gilts, remained strong, although last
year's net investment of Pounds 13.2bn fell short of 1992's record Pounds
15.4bn net total.
Looked at by institutional group, the CSO figures show that all groups,
apart from pension funds, increased their net investment last year. The
increase was particularly marked for unit trusts which enjoyed their best
ever year for inflows from private investors. Net investment by unit trusts
rose from Pounds 1.4bn in 1992, to a record Pounds 10.8bn last year.
In the fourth quarter, activity by investment trusts staged the most
striking pick-up. This partly reflected the launch of several new trusts at
the end of last year that took advantage of new legislation allowing
corporate investment in Lloyd's of London, the insurance market, for the
first time.
As a result, total net investment was a record Pounds 1.9bn in the fourth
quarter, compared with Pounds 66m in the third.
Net investment by pension funds increased slightly to Pounds 2.15bn in the
fourth quarter. This brought the total for the year to Pounds 8bn, a similar
level to the previous two years.
Net investment by unit trusts and property unit trusts at Pounds 2.6bn in
the fourth quarter was still at an exceptionally high level.
</TEXT>
