<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Mercury raises fears on BT 'superhighway'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mercury, the main competitor to British Telecommunications, yesterday
opposed construction of a national fibre-optic 'superhighway'.
However, it supported lifting the ban on BT providing entertainment services
in return for a more favourable regulatory regime.
Lord Young, chairman of Cable &amp; Wireless, Mercury's parent company, told the
Commons trade and industry committee that he favoured the development of
competing local networks to deliver services rather than a BT fibre-optic
monopoly at local level.
In the most detailed explanation yet of Mercury's plans to deploy wireless
technology to by-pass BT at the local level, Lord Young said Mercury
expected to have between 3m and 5m customers accessing its long-distance
network through radio links 'in a few years'.
The radio networks would be able to carry broadcast channels in addition to
telephony.
Lord Young told the committee, which is examining the case for a national
fibre-optic grid, that a grid 'would not bring any additional benefits for
business and residential customers'. Instead there should be 'a range of
competing technologies and competing operators'. He added: 'Britain has
advanced too far down the competitive road to revert to a utility-style
single national grid.'
Lord Young renewed Mer-cury's call for a regulatory regime more favourable
to it, claiming the company would support a lifting of the ban on BT
carrying entertainment over its network before 1998 'provided we have
economic access to the BT network'.
Mercury is locked in a legal dispute with Oftel, the telecommunications
regulator, about terms for inter-connection to the BT network, which it
believes are unduly restrictive.
The Cable Television Association also opposed a national fibre grid. It
represents the - mostly US - cable companies building combined cable TV and
telephone networks in urban areas.
</TEXT>
