<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Rival to Coke may go to Sainsbury
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A new cola brand which could revolutionise the Pounds 1.2bn retail market
for carbonated drinks in the UK may be launched in May by J. Sainsbury, the
UK's biggest grocery chain.
Cott Corporation, the fast growing Canadian marketing and bottling company,
said yesterday that it was at an advanced stage of negotiations with
Sainsbury on a proposal to launch a 'sub-brand' which would incorporate both
the Sainsbury logo and a new marque.
Mr Simon Lester of Cott said the peak selling time for carbonated drinks was
at the end of May. The group wanted any launch to be before that time.
Over the past three years Cott has captured about 20 per cent of the
Canadian cola market and 2 per cent of the US market through the launch of
supermarket sub-brands. Its share price has increased 100-fold over the same
period.
Sainsbury would aim to produce a better quality cola than traditional
supermarket brands and sell it for a higher price, although it would be
cheaper than Coca Cola or Pepsi Cola, which are about Pounds 1 for two
litres.
Mr Lester said Sainsbury and Cott were considering a series of possible
names for the new brand. They included variations of marques used by Cott in
the US and Canada, such as Sam's American Choice, Select and President's
Choice. Another possibility is Classic.
Coca Cola's leading US brand is called Classic and the company said it would
sue for breach of copyright if Sainsbury were to borrow any of its names or
package the product in a way which was too close to its own packaging.
Sainsbury refused to comment on the negotiations.
</TEXT>
