<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / MPs seek reform of university spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sloppy purchasing procedures cost the 'old' universities in England at least
Pounds 30m per year, the cross-party Commons public accounts committee says
in a report issued yesterday.
It recommends reforms to universities' financial management, and calls on
the Higher Education Funding Council for England, an education department
quango, to take the lead in ensuring the savings were made. The figure
excludes 'new' universities recently converted from polytechnics.
The report says: 'We note the acceptance by the higher education sector that
savings of at least 5 per cent are achievable from improved purchasing
practices, equivalent to over Pounds 30m each year for the old universities
sector in England alone.'
It found that large numbers of staff had purchasing responsibilities, and
that 'in some universities there were lapses in the fundamental requirement
that an invoice should be authorised for payment by a different person to
that raising the related purchasing order'.
The committee recommends publishing comparisons on prices paid for a
'substantial basket of goods'. Research shows that could have saved 5 per
cent if they all bought 27 commonly used items at their average price.
Professor Graeme Davies, chief executive of the funding council, welcomed
the report. He said it would allow further progress to be made, but he added
that universities had achieved savings of Pounds 1.7bn since 1988-89 by
'expanding their student numbers without a proportionate increase in public
funding'.
University Purchasing in England, Committee of Public Accounts. HMSO. Pounds
8.10.
</TEXT>
