<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Short Lautro test that 'a monkey could pass': How sales
staff are trained
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ms Gillian Hurley spent what she regards as 'the worst time of her life'
selling personal pensions and other life products.
She worked for Henley Financial Associates, a London-based company which
sells insurance on behalf of Lincoln National, a big US investment products
group.
Ms Hurley joined Henley in 1991 aged 20. After four weeks' sales training,
she travelled around south-east England by train and taxi selling investment
plans and pension products to doctors.
She left disillusioned after less than a year. Her earnings, worked out on a
commission basis, totalled no more than about Pounds 2,000.
Ms Hurley, who now works for a City investment group, says she never
knowingly gave misleading advice to clients but says that she never knew
enough about the products she was selling - and crucially their possible
disadvantages compared with other insurance products - to give best advice.
Yet she managed to satisfy the training standards laid down by Lautro, the
insurance industry watchdog, which were meant to ensure that people buying
pensions and related products got a good deal.
Because her salary was linked to sales Ms Hurley was under pressure to sell
as many products as she could. 'I learnt to bluff my way through many
situations where clients asked too many technical questions - dangerous
considering I was toying with the financial future of many people,' she
said.
'The product training I received was atrocious. (To satisfy the Lautro
requirement) I had to take a half-an-hour test that a monkey could have
passed.'
Critics of the life insurance industry say the high rate of turnover of
sales staff, with poor training standards and the emphasis on commission,
can often lead to consumers being sold inappropriate products.
According to industry estimates about half the 150,000 sales people in the
industry have been in their jobs for less than two years. Many believe their
training is inadequate given the complexity of the products they are
selling.
Mr Joel Joffe, former deputy chairman of insurance company Allied Dunbar and
an advocate of higher consumer standards, said: 'The industry has in recent
years increased the competence of its sales staff, but more needs to be
done.'
Ms Janet Trimmer, who left the industry last year after 10 years as an
insurance consultant, said: 'Companies will take on just about anyone as
long as they don't have a criminal record.'
The industry can point to many sales staff who are happy with their
conditions of employment and believe they do a valuable job, but it is not
difficult to find other people with experiences similar to those of Ms
Hurley.
Mr Simon Evans, who worked for Henley for 18 months in the early 1990s and
is now an independent financial adviser, said that the product training at
Henley failed to cover what was available in the industry. As a result the
products he was selling 'may not necessarily have been the best ones' to
suit particular customers.
Ms Margaret Kinlay, head of sales at Henley, which employs 50 staff in three
offices around Britain, said she was 'sorry and surprised' to hear the
complaints about training standards.
She said: 'In the past Lautro has told us we were well ahead of what is
required.'
Mr Derek Rogers, marketing director at the UK subsidiary of Lincoln
National, said his company insisted on rigorous training standards. Henley
had a very good training record.
Another person with a less than glowing tale of his experiences in the
industry is Mr Richard Butler, who worked for two months from December 1990
at the Southend on Sea, Essex, office of the Laurentian Milldon insurance
group.
On the dole at the time, Mr Butler, aged 23, answered an advertisement in
his local paper calling for sales staff. He said his four weeks of training
emphasised not the products but sales procedures.
'You had to say to the customer: 'You know it makes sense.' If they nodded
their heads or said 'yes' you were on the way to making a sale. I had to
pass a test to meet the Lautro standards, but it was dead easy. You were
asked a set of questions 10 minutes after having been told what the answers
were.'
After earning Pounds 1,400 selling three investment plans, Mr Butler left
Laurentian having realised that the insurance business was not for him.
Laurentian said all its 450 sales staff received 'intensive training' and
that had Mr Butler stayed with the company he would have been put through
more rigorous training procedures to increase his knowledge of the industry.
</TEXT>
<XX>
