<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Debt trading reform rejected in Bank U-turn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of England yesterday 'firmly rejected' its own controversial
suggestion that lenders be prohibited from trading the debt of companies
while a financial restructuring is taking place.
The Bank, after discussions with British bankers, has decided that even a
formal code of practice governing sales of distressed company debt is
unwise.
The Bank has been concerned that the ability of creditors to sell loans in
the secondary market - and the ability of other investors to buy them -
could disrupt efforts to find arrangements which would allow a viable
company to continue trading. It has asked banks to try to secureco-operation
between a troubled company and all its lenders.
Mr Pen Kent, executive director at the Bank of England, said at a conference
on distressed debt: 'One of the ideas initially mooted by myself in earlier
speeches was the idea of a closed season on trading to avoid disruption at
sensitive times. After a fairly wide discussion among a range of banks, both
British and foreign, this has now been firmly rejected.'
Mr Kent said, however, that banks remained free to agree among themselves to
restrict trading during sensitive periods, either when they were drawing up
loan documentation or when a borrower's difficulties became apparent.
Mr Kent also said that after considerable discussion the Bank had decided
against formally codifying best practice for those trading distressed
corporate debt.
Instead, Mr Kent said, the Bank was outlining the spirit of the 'London
approach' - co-operation between banks and lenders - and asking debt traders
to honour it. Specifically, debt trading should occur in a 'positive and
constructive spirit', potential investors should be informed of the London
approach before buying debt and institutions should inform fellow lenders
when they intend to sell debt.
Also, the Bank wants further discussions relating to such matters as inside
information. It wants clarification on how much about a company's affairs
can be revealed to potential investors by existing lenders.
Debt traders welcomed the statement. Mr Peter Young, head of loan trading at
Continental Bank said: 'The Bank has probably come to the view that trading
in distressed debt is valuable for the market and actually helps liquidity.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
