<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Swan Hunter rescue still in balance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The prospects of Swan Hunter, the Tyneside shipbuilder in receivership,
finding a buyer were still in the balance last night after a day of
intensive negotiations between French-owned Constructions Mecaniques de
Normandie and Swan Hunter receivers Price Waterhouse.
CMN had hoped to bid for Swan Hunter before today's Ministry of Defence
deadline for submission of tenders for the refit of the landing ship Sir
Bedivere. However no bid was made yesterday.
Joint receiver Mr Gordon Horsfield said last night that he was hopeful of
seeing a sale within the next few days, although any agreement with CMN was
likely to be conditional on winning the refit.
Price Waterhouse said it would today submit to the MoD its tender for the
refit. It described the contract as critical to the yard's survival.
For the tender to have any chance of success, it must be underwritten by a
prospective buyer for Swan Hunter. To maintain the bid's credibility the
underwriting needs to take place within a matter of days.
Price Waterhouse did not rule out the possibility of another bidder coming
forward.
Mr Fred Henderson, leader of the CMN bid team, said: 'Our interest is in
buying Swan Hunter as a viable, continuing business, although some
negotiation has still to be done.' He confirmed that any offer would be
conditional on winning the Sir Bedivere tender.
The importance of a bid from CMN - the only company to say publicly that it
wants to buy the yard - was heightened yesterday by news from
Southampton-based shipbuilder Vosper Thornycroft that it felt there were
'insufficient grounds' for it to make an offer at this stage. It said it
would keep the position under review.
Earlier this week CMN insisted that it must have categorical government
assurances that if it bought Swan Hunter it would be treated equally with
other, UK-owned, shipyards in the fight for future MoD contracts.
The MoD said it had given general assurances and added that a specific
letter to CMN might be sent 'in the very near future'.
</TEXT>
