<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Advertisers go to work on the egg
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
From next Monday morning breakfasters will be able to read their boiled eggs
as well as their newspapers - British Telecommunications has taken
advertising space on 13.5m eggs to promote its new daytime phone charges.
BT said the eggs, which will bear the message 'Wake up to BT's new Daytime
Rate', were a 'cheap medium' enabling it to get over the message that peak
charges have been abolished.
European ministers failed to agree in September last year on whether
advertising on eggs should be allowed - but gave the go-ahead for a two-year
trial.
Holmes &amp; Marchant Blitz, the advertising agency which is producing the egg
campaign for BT, said it was the first large-scale promotion using
advertisements on eggs in Europe. It believed egg advertising had been tried
in Israel.
The advertisements are printed using a high-pressure jet which blows dots of
food colouring on each shell.
More than 20 packaging stations have been equipped to print the patented
'eggverts'.
The eggs will be distributed through Tesco and Asda supermarkets in time for
Easter.
</TEXT>
