<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / World Trade News: Ford set to make parts in China
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ford, the US vehicle-maker, has reached outline agreement with Shanghai
Automotive Industry Corporation (SAIC) to set up a components joint venture
in China.
It would be Ford's first manufacturing venture in China, and the company
said it hoped to go ahead 'as soon as possible'.
The two companies expect to finalise the deal 'in a few weeks'. It will then
be submitted to the authorities for final approval.
The collaboration between Ford's plastic and trim products division and
SAIC's Yan Feng division is aimed at producing a range of components
including interior trim, seats, instrument panels and other plastic parts
for the Chinese motor industry.
Ford said that Yan Feng was currently the largest supplier of automotive
trim components in China.
The US company is also having discussions with several other Chinese
manufacturers that could lead to components joint ventures in areas such as
glass, electronics, engine management systems and air conditioning. It said
it was also interested in vehicle assembly opportunities in China.
</TEXT>
