FT  24 MAR 94 / Clinton plans to speak out on Whitewater
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton will tonight hold perhaps the most important
televised press conference of his presidency. The White House expects it to
be dominated by the Whitewater affair, reports Jurek Martin from Washington.
The president is concerned by the extent to which the first family's
financial investments in Arkansas has deflected attention from his domestic
agenda. The broadcast gives him an opportunity to go over the heads of a
suspicious Washington political and media establishment to assure a national
audience only dimly aware of Whitewater that he has committed no wrongdoing
and is co-operating with all investigations.
Both houses of Congress have called for fully fledged hearings into
Whitewater.
