<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Finnish territorial water move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HELSINKI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Finland intends to extend its territorial waters to 12 nautical miles from
the present four, the Finnish news agency STT reported yesterday. It said
the centre-right government made the decision at a meeting and a proposal
would be submitted to parliament before the middle of the year. A corridor
of international waters at least six nautical miles wide would remain
between Finland and Estonia in the Gulf of Finland that leads to the Russian
city of St Petersburg. One reason behind the move is to help Finnish
authorities check cross-border traffic to prevent smuggling and other crime.
It would also help efforts to protect the marine environment. Neighbouring
Sweden extended its waters in 1979 and Estonia decided about a year ago to
do the same.
