<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 94 / Lyell resists 'scapegoat' role in arms affair
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Nicholas Lyell, the attorney-general, last night launched a dramatic
effort to defend his role in the political furore over arms-related sales to
Iraq by insisting he would not be a 'scapegoat' in the affair.
In a series of television interviews before his appearance today at the
inquiry headed by Lord Justice Scott, Sir Nicholas vigorously defended his
role in seeking to prevent critical Whitehall documents being released to a
trial of three businessmen.
Sir Nicholas admitted in an interview with ITN that he had at one stage
considered resigning, but said he had rejected the idea. 'If I thought I had
done something wrong at the outset, that would have been the time to have
resigned - when the case collapsed. I thought about that carefully at the
time,' he said. But his appearance on television just ahead of evidence to
the Scott inquiry underlined the serious threat the affair poses to the
attorney-general's political future.
'I hope not to be the fall guy because I believe in justice and I believe I
advised carefully,' Sir Nicholas said. He added: 'I certainly don't believe
I am beleaguered by colleagues.'
In his interview with the BBC, he said: 'I don't believe in scapegoats, and
I am confident that what I did was right and fair and carefully done.'
Sir Nicholas has been under intense pressure since Mr Michael Heseltine, the
trade and industry secretary, told the inquiry earlier this month that he
had strongly resisted an instruction from the attorney-general to withhold
documents from the Matrix Chirchill trial.
Mr Heseltine and three other ministers eventually signed the so-called
public interest immunity certificates. But Sir Nicholas's judgment in
issuing the instruction has been strongly criticised by leading legal
authorities.
The attorney-general said last night that he had 'nothing against Mr
Heseltine at all'.
He said: 'I quite understand that from different perspectives, people see
things differently.' But he added: 'I gave him careful written advice.'
Sir Nicholas defended himself against the idea that, as attorney-general, he
had taken a party political view in the whole affair.
'When it comes to prosecutions, party politics has nothing to do with it
whatsoever. That is the job of attorneys-general down the centuries,' he
said.
'They have been criticised down the centuries. We have been like lighthouses
in a storm for a very, very long time. I am proud to be there and I intend
to stand like a lighthouse.'
Sir Nicholas said there were 'real lessons' to be learned from the affair.
'I look forward to getting across to the world this complete and utter myth
about me and about all the perfectly responsible ministers who signed these
certificates,' he said.
</TEXT>
